\begin_layout Subsection
Supply side
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Public production, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\text{Pub},t}$
\end_inset

, is produced just as private sector goods are, in the sense that it uses
 labor, capital equipment and structures, and intermediate inputs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most public services are not traded on a market, however, and therefore
 no market prices exist in the data.
 The accounting price of public production is instead the average cost of
 production rather than a market price.
 This is equivalent to saying that there are zero profits in the public
 sector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The default setting in MAKRO is that all factors of public production (labor,
 capital equipment and structures, and intermediate inputs) are exogenous.
 The quantity of output produced is endogenous, but only reacts to shocks
 to the production factors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total cost of public production is the sum of the value of the inputs
 into production: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{\text{Pub},t}^{Y}Y_{\text{Pub},t}=w_{t}\rho_{\text{Pub},t}h_{\text{Pub},t}n_{\text{Pub},t}+\sum_{k}P_{k,\text{Pub},t}^{I}\delta_{k,\text{Pub},t-1}K_{k,\text{Pub},t-1}+P_{\text{Pub},t}^{R}R_{\text{Pub},t}+T_{\text{Pub},t}^{\text{NetY}}\label{eq:public_production_value}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}\rho_{\text{Pub},t}h_{\text{Pub},t}n_{\text{Pub},t}$
\end_inset

 is the public sector payroll, and where following accounting standards
 for the public sector, the cost of public capital is entirely accounted
 for as depreciation
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In years covered by data, we include residual terms in the depreciation
 rates and prices used to compute the value of public capital depreciation
 in order to match the national accounts data.
 Public capital depreciation would otherwise differ slightly from the national
 accounts data due to composition effects in the prices of capital and investmen
t which affect the chain indices used to calculate prices.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Net production taxes and subsidies, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\text{Pub},t}^{\text{NetY}}$
\end_inset

, are added explicitly rather than being included in the payroll and cost
 of capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the total cost of public production, the issue is how to measure separatel
y the quantity of public output, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\text{Pub},t},$
\end_inset

 and its price 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\text{Pub},t}^{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 In our model of the private sector we solve this problem using a theory
 of production.
 This is materialized in a (CES) production function that describes how
 the quantities of inputs are organized to generate units of output.
 The output price is then a by-product of this theory and of profit maximization.
 For the public sector, we generally do not apply a standard theory of productio
n, but instead apply the 
\emph on
input method
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Input method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have separate measures of the price and quantity of each factor input
 in public production.
 We can measure investment, capital stocks, employment, and quantities of
 intermediate inputs used.
 From these, we create a Paasche price index of the underlying factor prices
 (set to 1 in the base year) and a corresponding Laspeyres measure of the
 quantity, so that in addition to eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:public_production_value"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
P_{\text{Pub},t-1}^{Y}Y_{\text{Pub},t}=\gamma_{t}w_{t-1}\rho_{\text{Pub},t-1}h_{\text{Pub},t}n_{\text{Pub},t}\\
+\sum_{k}P_{k,\text{Pub},t-1}^{I}\delta_{k,\text{Pub},t-1}K_{k,\text{Pub},t-1}+P_{\text{Pub},t-1}^{R}R_{\text{Pub},t}+\frac{T_{\text{Pub},t-1}^{\text{NetY}}}{Y_{\text{Pub},t-1}}Y_{\text{Pub},t}
\end{array}\label{eq:pYoff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the data, public employees are differentiated by educational attainment
 etc., and changes in the average public wage may therefore reflect changes
 in the composition of public employees rather than actual changes in wages
 for the individual public employee.
 E.g.
 the average public wage increases if the share of highly educated workers
 increases, even if the wage pr.
 highly educated worker remains constant.
 An additional exogenous term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{t}$
\end_inset

, is included with the lagged wage to capture this effect in the baseline
 forecast.
 In addition, in years covered by data, this term also captures differences
 between the input method and the national accounting estimates of public
 production, which attempts to measure actual output (number of surgeries
 etc.).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The chain index method of accounting for public production has the unfortunate
 feature that a shock which leaves all factors of public production completely
 unchanged can still affect the Laspeyres measure of output through price
 changes.
 For a transitory shock, the effect is negligible, but for a permanent shock
 the effect can be difficult to ignore, as the effect accumulates over time.
 The problem also exists for other chain indices, but is exacerbated here
 by the fact that capital and intermediate inputs generally follow productivity
 growth, while hours worked do not.
 For shocks to the model, which do not affect any public sector factor of
 production, users are therefore advised to also exogenize government consumptio
n, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}$
\end_inset

, rather than using eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pYoff"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Public employment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expenditure on labor by the public sector consists of wages paid pr.
 hour, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}\rho_{\text{Pub},t}$
\end_inset

, times hours pr.
 employee, 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\text{Pub},t}$
\end_inset

, times the number of employee, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{Pub},t}$
\end_inset

.
 Payroll taxes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}^{L}$
\end_inset

, are disregarded here as they are transfers from the state to itself.
 The wage expenditure also disregards vacancy posting costs as these are
 a component of the user cost of labor, which is not considered in the input
 method of accounting for the public sector.
 I.e.
 since we merely measure costs, rather than apply a standard theory of productio
n, it does not matter whether the labor is spent as hiring costs or used
 in production.
 The hourly wage, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}\rho_{\text{Pub},t}$
\end_inset

, is detailed in the labor market chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Public employment in hours is exogenous by default in MAKRO.
 In the baseline forecast, the ratio between public capital and output is
 fixed, as well as the ratio between the public payroll and expenditure
 on intermediate purchases (we go into detail on these ratios below).
 With the public K/Y and L/R ratios fixed in the baseline, public employment
 is determined residually given a baseline demand for public production.
 The baseline demand for public production is covered in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Demand-for-public"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Public investments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Public investments as real quantities are exogenous by default in MAKRO,
 and it is up to the user to shock public investments explicitly for a balanced
 shock to public production.
 Public sector capital (equipment and structures) obeys the standard law
 of motion
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{k,\text{Pub},t}=\left(1-\delta_{k,\text{Pub},t}\right)K_{k,\text{Pub},t-1}+I_{k,\text{Pub},t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the baseline forecast, public investments are determined residually as
 we forecast the public sector capital stock directly.
 Public sector capital in current investment prices is forecasted as a constant
 share, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{k,t}^{K}$
\end_inset

, of a weighed average of public and private sector gross value added.
 That is, we add the restriction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{k,t}^{I}K_{k,t}=\hat{\alpha}_{k,t}^{K}\left(0.7\cdot\left(P_{\text{Pub},t}^{Y}Y_{\text{Pub},t}-P_{\text{Pub},t}^{R}R_{\text{Pub},t}\right)+0.3\cdot X_{t}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a moving average of private sector value added.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{k,t}^{K}$
\end_inset

 is constant in the baseline forecast, but is endogenous by default for
 shocks to the model as public investments are fixed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
New, direct, and indirect investments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to distinguishing between capital structures and equipment,
 public investments are also classified in three other categories: 
\emph on
new
\emph default
,
\emph on
 direct
\emph default
,
\emph on
 
\emph default
and 
\emph on
indirect 
\emph default
investments.
 In this section we document how these categories are allocated between
 equipment and structures and how we forecast these categories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The majority of public investments are categorized as 
\emph on
new investments
\emph default
, and we divide these between both capital types with a share parameter,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}^{new}$
\end_inset

.
 Direct investments, which consist almost entirely of publicly funded R&D
 are allocated to investments in equipment.
 Finally, indirect investments are purchases of existing capital and are
 entirely allocated to structures.
 In current prices, we have the following accounting identities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{public investments}_{t}=\text{new investments}_{t}+\text{direct investments}_{t}+\text{indirect investments}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{public investment in structures}_{t}=\mu_{t}^{new}\cdot\text{new investments}_{t}+\text{indirect investments}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{public investment in equipment}_{t}=\left(1-\mu_{t}^{new}\right)\cdot\text{new investments}_{t}+\text{direct investments}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indirect investments are modeled as a constant share of aggregate gross
 value added
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{indirect investments}_{t}=\mu_{t}^{indirect}\cdot\left(P_{t}^{Y}Y_{t}-P_{t}^{R}R_{t}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the separation between indirect and new investments is purely
 accounting and has no effect on any behavior in MAKRO.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Direct investments are modeled as a fixed share of public production in
 real quantities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{direct investments}_{t}=P_{\text{Pub},t}^{Y}\cdot\mu_{iM,t}^{\text{Pub}}\cdot Y_{\text{Pub},t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New investments are determined residually, given total public investments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Intermediate input purchases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aggregate quantity of intermediate inputs used in public production
 is exogenous by default in MAKRO.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intermediate inputs in the public sector are sourced from many production
 sectors, both domestic and foreign, in exactly the same way as other demand
 components and is covered in the input/output chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the baseline forecast we assume a constant ratio, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}^{LR}$
\end_inset

, between the public payroll and expenditures on intermediate inputs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{t}^{LR}=\frac{w_{t}\rho_{\text{Pub},t}h_{\text{Pub},t}n_{\text{Pub},t}}{P_{\text{Pub},t}^{R}R_{\text{Pub},t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a generic shock to government consumption, the user can exogenize this
 ratio in order to determine a proportional change in public sector intermediate
 purchases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Demand for public production
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Demand-for-public"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Public production, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\text{Pub},t}$
\end_inset

, is given in the input/output system as the sum of three demand components:
 government consumption (of public services) 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{\text{Pub}}$
\end_inset

, private consumption of public services 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\text{Pub}}$
\end_inset

, and public direct investments, 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{\text{Pub}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{\text{Pub},t}=C_{t}^{\text{Pub}}+G_{t}^{\text{Pub}}+I_{t}^{\text{Pub}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we assume that the same price (before taxes) is paid independent of how
 output is consumed, this identity holds both for real quantities and in
 current prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Private consumption of public services and public direct investments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model the private consumption of public services as proportional to governmen
t consumption:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{c,t}^{\text{Pub}}=\mu_{c,t}^{\text{Pub}}G_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The underlying assumption is that the structure of public services are fixed,
 such that co-payments remain a constant share except if the user shocks
 these structures explicitly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, public direct investments (R&D) are a fixed share of public productio
n:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{k,t}^{\text{Pub}}=\mu_{k,t}^{\text{Pub}}Y_{\text{Pub},t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two assumptions imply that public production is fixed except for shocks
 that affect the government consumption, as opposed to moving endogenously
 with changes in private sector demand through constant input/output shares.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Government consumption of public production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total government consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the sum of government consumption of public output plus government consumpti
on of private output, including imports (the blue column in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:PublicProductionIO"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{t}^{G}G_{t}=P_{G,Pub,t}^{Y\tau}G_{t}^{Pub}+\text{Private inputs}=\sum_{s}\left(P_{G,s,t}^{Y\tau}Y_{G,s,t}+P_{G,s,t}^{M\tau}M_{,G,s,t}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sourcing of government consumption from different sectors, domestic
 and foreign, works in exactly the same way as other demand components and
 is covered in the input/output chapter.
 Given a desired total government consumption, the input/output system delivers
 a demand for public production, or vice versa given a total public production,
 we can calculate total government consumption as a residual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As all factors of production are fixed by default, the supply of public
 production 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\text{Pub},t}$
\end_inset

 is also effectively fixed, and the demand for government consumption is
 determined residually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Baseline government consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We decompose the costs of government consumption in two parts: the depreciation
 costs of capital and the remainder:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{t}^{G}G_{t}=\sum_{k}\delta_{\text{Pub},k,t}P_{\text{Pub},k,t}^{I}K_{\text{Pub},k,t}+\mu_{t}^{G}N_{t}^{G}\rho_{t}w_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the baseline, the remainder (government consumption net of depreciations),
 follow a fixed 
\emph on
government service level
\emph default
 parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}^{G}$
\end_inset

, times an exogenous demographics based index of demand of government services,
 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}^{G}$
\end_inset

, and finally the average wage 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}\cdot w_{t}$
\end_inset

 pr.
 hour, in line with the forecast methodology of the Ministry of Finance.
 The demographics index is an important exogenous input to the model baseline
 and based on more detailed demographic projections (befolkningsregnskab).
\end_layout

