\begin_layout Subsubsection
Productivity Growth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is assumed the there is no labor augmenting technological progress in
 the public sector.
 A simple way to understand the consequences of this fact is to work as
 if public production happened through a Cobb-Douglas production function
 with inputs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(K_{b},K_{m},L,R\right)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=K_{b,t}^{\alpha_{b}^{K}}K_{m,t}^{\alpha_{m}^{K}}\left(A_{t}L_{t}\right)^{\alpha^{L}}R_{t}^{\alpha^{R}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In such a case the price would be the variable recovered through the zero
 profit condition, and this price would be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{t}=A_{t}^{-\alpha^{L}}\left(\frac{P_{b,t}^{K}}{\alpha_{b}^{K}}\right)^{\alpha_{b}^{K}}\left(\frac{P_{m,t}^{K}}{\alpha_{m}^{K}}\right)^{\alpha_{m}^{K}}\left(\frac{P_{t}^{L}}{\alpha^{L}}\right)^{\alpha^{L}}\left(\frac{P_{t}^{R}}{\alpha^{R}}\right)^{\alpha^{R}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a balanced growth path all input prices or user costs grow with the inflation
 rate, except for the user cost of labor, which increases with the inflation
 rate plus the Harrod neutral growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\xi}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies for a Cobb-Douglas output price:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{P_{t}}{P_{t-1}}=\left(1+\pi\right)^{\alpha_{b}^{K}+\alpha_{m}^{K}+\alpha^{R}}\left(\frac{\left(1+\pi\right)\left(1+g_{\xi}\right)}{\left(1+g_{\xi}\right)}\right)^{\alpha^{L}}=1+\pi
\]

\end_inset

It is, however, assumed that there is no productivity growth in the public
 sector.
 This implies that its price will grow with a higher rate, namely
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{P_{t}^{0}}{P_{t-1}^{0}}=\left(1+\pi\right)^{\alpha_{b}^{K}+\alpha_{m}^{K}+\alpha^{R}}\left(\frac{\left(1+\pi\right)\left(1+g_{\xi}\right)}{1}\right)^{\alpha^{l}}=\left(1+\pi\right)\left(1+g_{\xi}\right)^{\alpha^{L}}
\]

\end_inset

where the contribution of the growth rate of technology on the labor price
 is weighed by the labor share.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is captured in the price index of public production by adding the growth
 of technology in the denominator as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{t}^{0}=P_{t-1}^{0}\frac{\sum_{i\in(b,m)}P_{i,t}^{I}K_{i,t}+P_{t}^{R}R_{t}+\left(P_{t}^{L}/\cancel{A_{t}}\right)\left(\cancel{A_{t}}L_{t}\right)}{\sum_{i\in(b,m)}P_{i,t-1}^{I}K_{i,t}+P_{t-1}^{R}R_{t}+\left(P_{t-1}^{L}/A_{t-1}\right)\left(A_{t}L_{t}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

and this works in the desired way because the technology factor grows at
 a constant rate in all sectors except for the public sector where it is
 constant.
\end_layout

